475
00:27:17,084 --> 00:27:20,850
What we could do is continue
with Greg "the Angel of Death's" version.

476
00:27:21,021 --> 00:27:22,386
That's plagiarism.

477
00:27:22,556 --> 00:27:24,649
Yes. Yes, yes. Good. Excellent.

478
00:27:24,825 --> 00:27:27,419
I would never in a million years
use someone else's work.

479
00:27:27,594 --> 00:27:28,788
I'm very glad you agree.

480
00:27:28,962 --> 00:27:34,559
So, what we need,
we need something brand-new.

481
00:27:35,669 --> 00:27:39,070
- So let's see. A song for Cora.
- Yes.

482
00:27:39,239 --> 00:27:43,039
- Has to be called "A Way Back Into Love."
- Correct.

483
00:27:43,210 --> 00:27:45,508
And it has to be something
Cora would sing about.

484
00:27:45,679 --> 00:27:46,941
Good.

485
00:27:47,114 --> 00:27:49,275
And it has to be something
you would sing about.

486
00:27:49,449 --> 00:27:50,609
Good, yeah.

487
00:27:50,784 --> 00:27:53,947
- What would you sing about?
- Whatever gets me the job, really.

488
00:27:54,521 --> 00:27:56,887
Oh, that's inspiring.

489
00:28:02,262 --> 00:28:06,699
Okay. Two people
searching for love, for salvation.

490
00:28:06,867 --> 00:28:08,164
Good, good, I love that.

491
00:28:08,335 --> 00:28:11,702
Love lost, love found.

492
00:28:12,339 --> 00:28:13,670
Love lost again.

493
00:28:13,840 --> 00:28:17,469
Yes, this is starting to sound
a little bit like luggage, but good.

494
00:28:36,163 --> 00:28:37,721
Thanks. That's really helpful.

495
00:28:38,332 --> 00:28:40,664
It doesn't have to be perfect.
Just spit it out.

496
00:28:40,834 --> 00:28:43,234
- They're just lyrics.
- "Just lyrics"?

497
00:28:44,237 --> 00:28:47,866
Lyrics are important.
They're just not as important as melody.

498
00:28:49,209 --> 00:28:50,870
I really don't think you get it.

499
00:28:51,345 --> 00:28:53,210
Oh, you look angry. Click your pen.

500
00:28:53,380 --> 00:28:56,315
A melody is like seeing someone
for the first time.

501
00:28:56,483 --> 00:28:58,348
The physical attraction. Sex.

502
00:28:58,952 --> 00:29:00,817
I so get that.

503
00:29:00,988 --> 00:29:04,116
But then, as you get to know the person,
that's the lyrics.

504
00:29:04,291 --> 00:29:06,919
Their story. Who they are underneath.

505
00:29:07,594 --> 00:29:11,860
It's the combination of the two
that makes it magic.

506
00:29:12,032 --> 00:29:13,624
Let's go for a walk.

507
00:29:13,800 --> 00:29:16,769
- A walk? What, now?
- Yeah.

508
00:29:16,937 --> 00:29:21,271
Out on the streets you see things
and, you know, hear things and eat things.

509
00:29:21,441 --> 00:29:23,932
It all sort of unlocks your mind.

510
00:29:28,649 --> 00:29:30,310
This is good. This is good.

511
00:29:30,484 --> 00:29:32,748
When you hit a wall,
you gotta change the subject.

512
00:29:32,919 --> 00:29:34,216
So why did PoP break up?

513
00:29:34,388 --> 00:29:37,186
I mean, Rhonda told me
that you guys were friends growing up?

514
00:29:37,357 --> 00:29:39,689
We were, yes,
and then Colin met a new manager...

515
00:29:39,860 --> 00:29:42,090
...who convinced him
he was the star of the band.

516
00:29:42,262 --> 00:29:45,754
Shortly after, he left, taking the last
three songs we'd written together...

517
00:29:45,932 --> 00:29:49,698
...and putting them on his solo album
which went on to sell eight million records.

518
00:29:49,870 --> 00:29:52,532
But how did you deal with that?

519
00:29:52,706 --> 00:29:54,640
Oh, with drugs, alcohol...

520
00:29:54,808 --> 00:29:58,835
...and ultimately, my own solo album.

521
00:30:03,550 --> 00:30:04,778
Cool.

522
00:30:04,951 --> 00:30:07,511
This copy has been in the racks
for six years.

523
00:30:07,688 --> 00:30:09,417
- Come on.
- No, no. I check every week.

524
00:30:09,589 --> 00:30:12,057
You see, I made a little mark,
there on the back. See?

525
00:30:12,225 --> 00:30:15,058
It sold only 50,000 copies,
most of those to my mother.

526
00:30:15,228 --> 00:30:17,788
Rolling Stone called it
"a crass, contrived effort...

527
00:30:17,964 --> 00:30:20,489
...not even good enough
for a dentist chair."

528
00:30:21,968 --> 00:30:24,163
Well, I'm sure there were other reviews.

529
00:30:24,337 --> 00:30:26,737
There were, there were.
But none as good as that one.

530
00:30:26,907 --> 00:30:28,841
And they were right, by the way. Yeah.

531
00:30:31,311 --> 00:30:33,836
To cut a long story short,
I gave up trying to write...

532
00:30:34,014 --> 00:30:36,778
...lost an incredible amount of money
and then my apartment.

533
00:30:36,950 --> 00:30:39,976
Chris stuck by me, booked me
an '80s reunion night on Long Island.

534
00:30:40,153 --> 00:30:42,246
And suddenly, they liked me again.

535
00:30:42,422 --> 00:30:44,652
It was weird.
It was like I'd never been away.

536
00:30:44,825 --> 00:30:46,725
The audience was a tad older, as was I...

537
00:30:46,893 --> 00:30:50,158
...but we were very, very profoundly happy
to see each other again.

538
00:30:50,330 --> 00:30:53,163
And it went on from there.

539
00:30:53,333 --> 00:30:56,860
Cruises. Reunions. Knott's Berry Farm,
which I'm sure you're familiar with.

540
00:30:57,037 --> 00:31:00,734
Busch Gardens,
that's one of my big fixtures of the year.

541
00:31:00,907 --> 00:31:02,238
What else can I tell you?

542
00:31:02,409 --> 00:31:05,936
I really appreciate
you opening up to me like this.

543
00:31:07,380 --> 00:31:10,508
I know what it's like
to live with a shadow overhead.

544
00:31:14,221 --> 00:31:15,449
What?

545
00:31:17,824 --> 00:31:19,018
Shadow.

546
00:31:19,659 --> 00:31:24,323
I've been living with a shadow overhead

547
00:31:25,265 --> 00:31:27,495
Now, that's a nice melody, isn't it?

548
00:31:27,667 --> 00:31:29,464
- It's good.
- Thank you. Thank you.

549
00:31:29,636 --> 00:31:32,161
Mind you, what do you know?
You don't even like melody.

550
00:31:32,339 --> 00:31:34,000
I never said that.

551
00:31:34,174 --> 00:31:36,074
You prefer the lyrics.

552
00:31:36,243 --> 00:31:37,301
I don't trust you.

553
00:31:37,477 --> 00:31:38,842
Your turn, what's next?

554
00:31:39,813 --> 00:31:42,145
I think that we should get
some breakfast.

555
00:31:42,315 --> 00:31:45,113
Please, come on, we're finally
on a roll here. Listen again.

556
00:31:45,285 --> 00:31:49,051
I've been living with a shadow overhead

557
00:31:49,222 --> 00:31:52,385
There'll be no more rhymes until I'm fed

558
00:31:52,559 --> 00:31:54,083
Please, seriously, seriously.

559
00:31:54,261 --> 00:31:56,354
I've been living with a shadow overhead

560
00:31:56,530 --> 00:31:59,363
I could be inspired
With just a piece of bread

561
00:32:00,100 --> 00:32:02,159
- I have the perfect place.
- Wait a minute.

562
00:32:02,335 --> 00:32:03,666
It's just on the next corner.

563
00:32:03,837 --> 00:32:05,737
- Keep moving and keep writing.
- All right.

564
00:32:05,906 --> 00:32:09,467
I've been looking
For someone to shed some light

565
00:32:10,010 --> 00:32:11,807
- That's good. That's good.
- Yeah?

566
00:32:11,978 --> 00:32:13,843
Shadows and light. You're deep.

567
00:32:14,014 --> 00:32:16,847
Okay, we need two more lines
of Cora verse. What's next?

568
00:32:17,017 --> 00:32:18,348
Soph?

569
00:32:21,254 --> 00:32:22,243
Sophie?

570
00:32:23,757 --> 00:32:25,349
What are you doing?

571
00:32:25,525 --> 00:32:26,924
Nothing.

572
00:32:27,093 --> 00:32:31,086
I thought I saw someone,
but it wasn't him. So it's fine.

573
00:32:31,264 --> 00:32:34,665
- Oh, there he is.
- What?

574
00:32:34,835 --> 00:32:37,804
A very nice picture, though.
That's funny.

575
00:32:38,572 --> 00:32:41,905
Interestingly enough, I mean--
Well, it is a bookstore.

576
00:32:42,075 --> 00:32:44,236
- So, you know, that does happen.
- What?

577
00:32:45,812 --> 00:32:47,803
Gosh, where were we? Okay.

578
00:32:47,981 --> 00:32:49,278
Shadow overhead

579
00:32:49,449 --> 00:32:53,283
Okay, can I just say, with all due respect,
that you are clearly--

580
00:32:53,453 --> 00:32:55,421
What is the word?
--insane at this moment.

581
00:32:55,589 --> 00:32:58,422
And because, according to Chris,
we have less than 36 hours...

582
00:32:58,592 --> 00:33:01,720
...before Cora goes to do Leno,
at which point my career is over...

583
00:33:01,895 --> 00:33:07,299
...it would be infinitely better for me
if you were sane. So how can I help?

584
00:33:10,170 --> 00:33:11,330
Do you know this book?

585
00:33:14,241 --> 00:33:17,472
Sally Michaels? Yes, yes.
Big bestseller. Yes.

586
00:33:17,644 --> 00:33:19,737
- Have you read it?
- No, of course not.

587
00:33:19,913 --> 00:33:23,974
Last book I read was The Alex Fletcher Story
by the editors of Teen Dream Magazine.

588
00:33:26,019 --> 00:33:27,486
Why?

589
00:33:32,025 --> 00:33:35,119
I'm Sally Michaels.

590
00:33:37,697 --> 00:33:41,224
I saw that they were giving these courses
on writing at the New School...

591
00:33:41,401 --> 00:33:43,392
...so I signed up.

592
00:33:43,570 --> 00:33:46,971
And my teacher was Sloan Cates.

593
00:33:47,140 --> 00:33:49,131
Brilliant, handsome.

594
00:33:49,309 --> 00:33:52,540
The truth is, I was in love with him.

595
00:33:53,313 --> 00:33:55,338
And we began spending
every minute together.

596
00:33:55,515 --> 00:33:59,315
Which is why I was sort of surprised
when his fiancÃ©e showed up.

597
00:34:00,587 --> 00:34:04,114
Yeah, he never mentioned that
he was engaged to a history professor...

598
00:34:04,291 --> 00:34:06,725
...who was on a year-long sabbatical
in Spain.

599
00:34:06,893 --> 00:34:09,384
And when she popped in
for an unexpected visit...

600
00:34:09,562 --> 00:34:13,157
...it sort of turned into a reenactment
of the Inquisition.

601
00:34:13,600 --> 00:34:16,125
And that-- And that was that?
That was the end of that?

602
00:34:16,303 --> 00:34:18,396
Yeah. We never saw each other again.

603
00:34:18,571 --> 00:34:21,802
I dropped the class and a year later,
his new novel showed up.

604
00:34:22,208 --> 00:34:24,039
The Sally What's-it novel.

605
00:34:24,210 --> 00:34:26,940
"The tale of a student
with exalted literary aspirations...

606
00:34:27,113 --> 00:34:31,413
...who lures a brilliant writer into an affair
so she can take advantage of his connections.

607
00:34:31,918 --> 00:34:36,252
But when he tries to break it off,
she devotes herself to ruining his life."

608
00:34:36,589 --> 00:34:38,921
Well, I mean, that obviously wasn't you.

609
00:34:40,026 --> 00:34:45,862
Well, she's a lit major from Long Island,
5'4", my color hair, all my habits.

610
00:34:46,032 --> 00:34:49,058
You know, talks to herself
and asks too many questions.

611
00:34:49,235 --> 00:34:51,669
Her parents founded
a weight reduction company...

612
00:34:51,838 --> 00:34:53,601
...that now her sister runs.

613
00:34:54,007 --> 00:34:55,941
Well, anyway, I...

614
00:34:56,676 --> 00:34:59,372
Since then, every time I pick up a pen...

615
00:34:59,546 --> 00:35:02,947
...I'm haunted by those words
that he wrote, you know?

616
00:35:03,116 --> 00:35:06,142
"She was a brilliant mimic." You know.

617
00:35:06,319 --> 00:35:09,117
"She could ape Dorothy Parker
or Emily Dickinson...

618
00:35:09,289 --> 00:35:12,452
...but stripped of someone else's
literary clothes...

619
00:35:12,625 --> 00:35:17,028
...she was a vacant,
empty imitation of a writer."

620
00:35:17,931 --> 00:35:20,923
First of all, you can't listen to some jerk.

621
00:35:21,434 --> 00:35:24,801
He's not a jerk.
He's a National Book Award winner.

622
00:35:24,971 --> 00:35:28,372
Well, then, get the best revenge,
write a hit song.

623
00:35:29,275 --> 00:35:32,472
Honestly, I don't think a pop song
is gonna impress Sloan Cates.

624
00:35:32,879 --> 00:35:35,677
Oh, no, of course not.
Pop is just for morons. Forgot that.

625
00:35:35,849 --> 00:35:39,114
- I didn't mean anything by it.
- Brain-dead, or taken too many drugs.

626
00:35:39,285 --> 00:35:41,310
You know what I'd say
to you and Sloan Cates?

627
00:35:41,488 --> 00:35:43,649
You can take all the novels
in the world...

628
00:35:43,823 --> 00:35:47,054
...and not one of them
will make you feel as good as fast as:

629
00:35:53,933 --> 00:35:55,901
That is real poetry. Those are real poets.

630
00:35:56,069 --> 00:36:00,096
Smokey Robinson, Stevie Wonder,
Bob Dylan, the Beatles.

631
00:36:00,273 --> 00:36:04,232
Okay. What if one of your heroes
came up to you and said--

632
00:36:04,411 --> 00:36:06,971
You know, Smokey, what if he said:

633
00:36:07,147 --> 00:36:10,947
"Alex Fletcher,
you are a horrible songwriter"?

634
00:36:11,117 --> 00:36:12,106
How would you react?

635
00:36:12,285 --> 00:36:15,948
I know Smokey a little bit. He's too nice
a gentleman ever to say such a thing.

636
00:36:17,023 --> 00:36:20,288
Dylan might. Dylan would, actually.
In fact, Dylan did.

637
00:36:20,460 --> 00:36:25,329
Okay, Dylan walks up to you and he says,
"You are a horrible songwriter."

638
00:36:26,699 --> 00:36:28,997
- How do you react?
- I would be horribly depressed.

639
00:36:29,169 --> 00:36:31,797
Yes. I would. I would.

640
00:36:31,971 --> 00:36:35,634
But then, after, you know,
months of brooding...

641
00:36:35,809 --> 00:36:38,642
...I would find a lyricist...

642
00:36:39,312 --> 00:36:42,907
...and write a song
about how horribly depressed I was.

643
00:36:43,083 --> 00:36:46,712
And it would be a big hit, everyone
would love me, and I'd make lots of money.

644
00:36:46,886 --> 00:36:49,582
Suddenly I'd be less depressed
than if I just sat around...

645
00:36:49,756 --> 00:36:53,123
...being a little bit self-indulgent,
letting my misery eat away at me...

646
00:36:53,293 --> 00:36:58,196
...until I'd become an emotional wreck
and creatively completely moribund.

647
00:37:00,533 --> 00:37:02,296
Yes, moribund.

648
00:37:06,673 --> 00:37:08,334
- Okay, let's go. Come on.
- All right.

649
00:37:08,975 --> 00:37:12,741
I've been living with a shadow overhead

650
00:37:12,912 --> 00:37:16,848
I've been sleeping
With a clown above my bed

651
00:37:17,016 --> 00:37:19,576
- "Clown" is not right. What is that word?
- It's "cloud."

652
00:37:19,752 --> 00:37:23,279
- Write more clearly. How can I--?
- Why would you have a clown in your bed?

653
00:37:23,456 --> 00:37:26,118
- It would not be the first time.
- Yeah, I'm not surprised.

654
00:37:26,292 --> 00:37:28,692
- Write in capital letters.
- Why don't you write it?

655
00:37:28,862 --> 00:37:31,296
I'm sorry, Khan.
We're gonna come back in one second.

656
00:37:31,464 --> 00:37:34,194
You dictate, I'll write.
And I will write like a human...

657
00:37:34,367 --> 00:37:36,426
...and not like a small Pekingese dog.

658
00:37:36,603 --> 00:37:39,731
What are you doing, you madwoman?
You're destroying my apartment.

659
00:37:39,906 --> 00:37:42,170
I can't write from across the room.

660
00:37:42,342 --> 00:37:45,140
Well, you're not writing here.
Get back to your corner.

661
00:37:45,311 --> 00:37:46,300
I can't have you here.

662
00:37:46,479 --> 00:37:49,937
- I'll be blocked. I'll be completely stuck.
- So go out the other side.

663
00:37:50,116 --> 00:37:52,175
I've never been the other side.

664
00:37:53,052 --> 00:37:56,351
Push, push. Push, push.

665
00:38:01,661 --> 00:38:03,788
Good. Better.

666
00:38:03,963 --> 00:38:07,091
You're still a fraction close.
Just-- Just back off, just one...

667
00:38:07,267 --> 00:38:08,757
Just-- Just--

668
00:38:08,935 --> 00:38:10,402
There, fine, good.

669
00:38:10,570 --> 00:38:12,060
Okay.

670
00:38:28,254 --> 00:38:31,087
And I don't think those chords are right.

671
00:38:31,257 --> 00:38:34,124
It has to sound different than the verse.

672
00:38:34,527 --> 00:38:36,518
What kind of different
did you have in mind?

673
00:38:36,696 --> 00:38:39,460
I don't know.
Something sadder, you know?

674
00:38:39,632 --> 00:38:42,863
And I still don't like my line
about "places in my mind."

675
00:38:43,036 --> 00:38:46,233
- It's fine.
- Fine isn't good.

676
00:38:46,406 --> 00:38:47,930
We only have time for fine.

677
00:38:48,107 --> 00:38:50,541
I tell you what.
We'll change "places in my mind"...

678
00:38:50,710 --> 00:38:53,110
...if I can keep the chord sequence
into the bridge.

679
00:38:53,279 --> 00:38:54,712
This isn't a negotiation.

680
00:38:54,881 --> 00:38:58,009
It's either right or wrong,
inspired or insipid.

681
00:38:58,184 --> 00:39:02,120
It's 4 in the morning. We're not writing the
last movement of the "Jupiter Symphony."

682
00:39:02,288 --> 00:39:05,314
It's a song for someone who's last hit
was "Welcome to Bootytown."

683
00:39:05,491 --> 00:39:06,788
Please, get back to work.

684
00:39:06,960 --> 00:39:09,656
I still don't like it.

685
00:39:09,829 --> 00:39:12,491
And it's "Entering Bootytown."

686
00:39:13,866 --> 00:39:16,334
And another thing,
the whole top section...

687
00:39:16,736 --> 00:39:19,034
I mean, it's so close.
We're just not there yet.

688
00:39:19,205 --> 00:39:21,605
We just-- We have to focus
and stay, you know...

689
00:39:21,774 --> 00:39:24,368
...completely understanding
of what we're trying to say.

690
00:39:24,544 --> 00:39:27,604
Okay, you may now
start killing the next one.

691
00:39:30,283 --> 00:39:35,516
All I wanna do
Is find a way back into love

692
00:39:39,092 --> 00:39:44,962
I can't make it through
Without a way back into love

693
00:39:51,204 --> 00:39:52,865
You know, I'm tone-deaf.

694
00:40:14,694 --> 00:40:16,958
Hey, what do you think of this?

695
00:40:17,130 --> 00:40:20,497
Just keep writing.
Cora is leaving in an hour.

696
00:40:46,492 --> 00:40:50,690
Listen, I was thinking that "corners"
was such a better word than "spaces."

697
00:40:50,863 --> 00:40:54,060
For "in the mind." "The corners
of my mind," rather than "the spaces."

698
00:40:54,233 --> 00:40:57,532
It just seems to have a better boundary
to it, you know?

699
00:40:57,704 --> 00:41:00,901
Should I speak to you
about this later? Okay.

700
00:41:10,216 --> 00:41:13,447
It sounds so good. I can't believe it.

701
00:41:13,619 --> 00:41:15,382
And now...

702
00:41:15,555 --> 00:41:17,022
...vocals.

703
00:41:17,190 --> 00:41:20,819
No, you see, you have to sing
into the microphone. It won't follow you.

704
00:41:20,993 --> 00:41:23,257
- But I can't.
- It's a duet for a man and a woman.

705
00:41:23,429 --> 00:41:24,953
We are as close as we've got.

706
00:41:25,131 --> 00:41:28,794
Your headphones and a level. You look nice.
You should wear them all the time.

707
00:41:28,968 --> 00:41:31,266
How is that?

